name: stillwater-national-wildlife-refuge-stillwater-wildlife-management-area-anaho-island-natio-53004
notes: The Fallon, Stillwater and Anaho Island National Wildlife Refuges are located in northwest Nevada and are administered by the refuge administrative office in Fallon, Nevada. Together they comprise the Stillwater Wildlife Management Area (SWMA). Water was a case of “feast and famine” in 1966. For the first two months, all units were full.  As the summer progressed, however, hot days and nights kept water consumption above supply.  Excessive salt accumulation reduced bulrush growth thus reducing food for ducks. Because of the poor water conditions and lack of food, many ducks went to wintering areas without stopping over. Botulism occurred only in a mild outbreak.  Development and maintenance on the refuge consisted of managing water facilities, improving road conditions and maintaining public facilities. The grazing program in 1966 was little changed from the previous year and was successful.
